    <title>Write-up Stolen Mount TryHackMe</title>
    <url>/archives/post/stolenMount/</url>
    <content><![CDATA[<p><span style="color:black;font-weight:bold;">Description:</span> An intruder has infiltrated our network and targeted the NFS server where the backup files are stored. A classified secret was accessed and stolen. The only trace left behind is a packet capture (PCAP) file recorded during the incident. Your mission, should you accept it, is to discover the contents of the stolen data.</p>
<p><span style="font-weight:bold;">First</span>, when we click ‘Start Machine’ we will see a <span style="font-weight:bold;">challenge.pcapng</span> file in the Desktop directory<br><span style="font-weight:bold;">Open with Wireshark </span>and we will see the following: </p>
<img  
                     lazyload
                     src="/images/loading.svg"
                     data-src="wireshark.png"
                      alt="Wireshark Capture" style="width:100%; border-radius:10px;"
                >

<p>Since the description mentioned NFS, we will filter this protocol. After filtering, I noticed that the info column contains the names of the <span style="color:black;font-weight:bold;">“procedures”</span> in the RPC protocol that NFS uses.</p>
<p>Searching on google, I found out that the procedure ‘READ’ is used to read the file, which may contain the file content or flag, so I searched for the keyword ‘READ’<br><img  
                     lazyload
                     src="/images/loading.svg"
                     data-src="filterpackage.png"
                      alt="Filter Package" style="width:100%; border-radius:10px;"
                ></p>
<p>After reading through the packets, I found that there are 2 important packets, packet 214 (containing archive password) and 286 (containing 1 secret.png image file in the .zip file because hex starts with &#x3D; 50 4b 03 04)</p>
<div style="text-align: center;">
  <img  
                     lazyload
                     src="/images/loading.svg"
                     data-src="package214.png"
                      alt="No. 214" style="width: 45%; display: inline-block; margin: 5px;"
                >
  <img  
                     lazyload
                     src="/images/loading.svg"
                     data-src="package286.png"
                      alt="No. 286" style="width: 47%; display: inline-block; margin: 5px;"
                >
</div>
Proceed to extract the zip file:
Right click on the packet -> Follow -> TCP Stream -> In the Show data as box -> Select Raw -> Save as... (secret.raw)

<p>Open terminal </p>
<div class="code-container" data-rel="Bash"><figure class="iseeu highlight bash"><table><tr><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">$ <span class="built_in">mv</span> secret.raw secret.zip</span><br><span class="line">$ unzip -l secret.zip</span><br><span class="line">$ unzip secret.zip</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></div>
<p>If successful, you will see a QR Code</p>
<blockquote>
<p><span style="color:red;font-style:italic;font-weight:bold;">Good Luck!!</span></p>
</blockquote>
]]></content>
